{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}} {{Infobox political party |name = The Animal Protection Party |logo = Animal Protection Party logo.gif |logo_size = 200px |colorcode = #A8E4A0 |leader = |chairperson = |president = |spokesperson = Sarah Coats, Carrie Holliman, Jim Kapetanos, and [[Keith Mann]] |foundation = {{startdate|2006|11|02|df=yes}} <ref name=ec/> |dissolved = {{enddate|2016|11|03|df=yes}} <ref name=ec>{{cite web|url=http://search.electoralcommission.org.uk/English/Registrations/PP601|title=Animal Protection Party|work=Electoral Commission|accessdate=April 15, 2017}}</ref> |ideology = [[Animal rights]] |headquarters = [[Bexleyheath]], [[Kent]], England |international = |website = [https://web.archive.org/web/*/www.animalprotectionparty.com The Animal Protection Party (archived)] |country = United Kingdom }} The '''Animal Protection Party''' ('''APP''') was a [[political party]] founded in [[England]] in 2006 to represent an [[animal rights]] perspective. It stood four candidates in the [[United Kingdom general election, 2010|2010 general election]]. The party de-registered in 2016.
==2010 general election== The APP stood in four constituencies in the [[United Kingdom general election, 2010|May 2010 British general election]], chosen because the sitting MP was viewed by the APP as representing the interests of people or industries that use animals.
*Sarah Coats, a recycling company administrator, stood in [[Meon Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Meon Valley]], a new constituency where [[Wickham Laboratories]] is based.<ref>{{cite new|url=http://www.portsmouth.co.uk/news/politics/sarah-coats-24-animal-protection-party-1-1249890|title=Sarah Coats, 24, Animal Protection Party|work=The News (Portsmouth)|date=April 21, 2010|accessdate=April 15, 2017}}</ref> Coats received 255 votes (0.3%); the seat was taken by [[George Hollingbery]] for the Conservatives.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/constituency/c84.stm Election 2010: Meon Valley], BBC, accessed May 7, 2010.</ref> *Carrie Holliman (listed by the Electoral Commission as the party leader)<ref name=ec/> stood in [[Huntingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Huntingdon]], where [[Huntingdon Life Sciences]] is based, against Conservative MP [[Jonathan Djanogly]]. She received 181 votes (0.3%). Djanogly held the seat.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/constituency/c30.stm Election 2010: Huntingdon], BBC, accessed May 7, 2010.</ref> *Jim Kapetanos stood in [[Vauxhall (UK Parliament constituency)|Vauxhall]] against the Labour MP [[Kate Hoey]], chair of the [[Countryside Alliance]], which promotes [[hunting]].<ref>[http://www.animalprotectionparty.com/index.php?id=5 Animal Protection Party: Elections] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091214195011/http://www.animalprotectionparty.com/index.php?id=5 |date=December 14, 2009 }}, accessed April 24, 2010.</ref> He received 96 votes (0.2%) and Hoey comfortably held the seat.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/constituency/e83.stm Election 2010: Vauxhall], BBC, accessed May 7, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.london-se1.co.uk/news/view/4528|title=Kate Hoey wins Vauxhall |work=London SE1|date=May 7, 2010|accessdate=April 15, 2017}}</ref> *[[Keith Mann]], who had previously been jailed for arson, stood in [[Oxford West and Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Oxford West and Abingdon]] against the Liberal Democrat MP [[Evan Harris]]; the area had been the focus of protests against the building of Oxford University's Biomedical Sciences Building.<ref>Ellery, Ben. [http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/news/8118038.Animal_rights_election_candidate_served_time_for_arson/ Animal rights election candidate served time for arson], ''Oxford Times'', April 24, 2010.</ref> Mann received 143 votes (0.3%); Harris lost the seat to [[Nicola Blackwood]] for the Conservative Party.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/constituency/d48.stm Election 2010: Oxford West & Abingdon], BBC, accessed May 7, 2010.</ref> Mann said "I wanted to challenge because of his support for animal testing in Oxford, but also because of his desire to extend the abortion time limit."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/general_election_2010/oxwest/8152627.ELECTION__Conservative_topples_Lib_Dem_Harris/|title=ELECTION: Conservative topples Lib Dem Harris|work=Oxford Times|last=Little|first=Reg|date=May 7, 2010|accessdate=April 15, 2017}}</ref>
