The '''Armed Forces Parliamentary Scheme''' ('''AFPS''') is a privately run programme to give [[Member of Parliament|Members of Parliament]] and peers in the [[United Kingdom]] and members of devolved assemblies, Tynwald and British MEPs experience of the [[armed forces]].  Its aim is to improve the quality of debate on military issues, and does this by exposing its members to first-hand experience of the service.<ref name="Tory MP Douglas Carswell">{{cite news |title=Tory MP Douglas Carswell 'punished' for damning army kit |first=Jonathan |last=Calvert |author2=Rowell, Andy |newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=31 August 2008 |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article4641398.ece }}</ref>

It was founded in 1989 by [[Neil Thorne|Sir Neil Thorne]], a former [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP,<ref name="Tory MP Douglas Carswell" /> for the benefit of members of both houses of [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] and those of all parties.  It is sponsored by three defence companies — [[BAE Systems]], [[Rolls-Royce plc|Rolls-Royce]], and [[AgustaWestland]] — which each contribute £45,000 a year.<ref name="Mr Bean's up in arms">{{cite news |title=Mr Bean's up in arms |first=Quentin |last=Letts |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |date=19 September 2009 |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-1214525/QUENTIN-LETTS-Can-Leather-weather-Tory-cut-throats.html }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmhansrd/cm070322/text/70322w0001.htm |title=Written Answers to Questions – Thursday 22 March 2007 |author= |date=22 March 2007 |work=[[Hansard]] |publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] |accessdate=16 May 2010}}</ref>

In 2008, Conservative MP [[Douglas Carswell]] was banned from the organisation after criticising the propriety of defence companies sponsoring it when he saw British soldiers under-equipped on the front line,<ref name="Tory MP Douglas Carswell" /> prompting questions about the programme's independence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicservice.co.uk/feature_story.asp?id=10331 |title=Questioning the scheme |first=Patrick |last=Macgill |date=5 September 2008 |work= |publisher=PSCA International |accessdate=16 May 2010 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  Sixteen MPs graduated from the AFPS in 2010,<ref>{{cite news |title=Service dinner: Armed Forces Parliamentary Scheme |first= |last= |newspaper=[[The Times]] |date=23 February 2010 |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/court_and_social/article7036751.ece }}</ref> and fifteen in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dinner: Armed Forces Parliamentary Scheme |first= |last= |newspaper=[[The Times]] |date=31 January 2009 |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/court_and_social/article5621907.ece }}</ref> MPs that participate in the AFPS for a long time can receive medals and honorary titles.<ref name="Mr Bean's up in arms" />

First year students are granted the honorary rank of Army - Major / RAF - Squadron Leader / RN - Lt Commander (depending on which branch of the armed forces they choose to join.  They are required to complete 22 days of service in order to graduate.  There are post graduate and further post graduate postings available, with honorary ranks of Lt Colonel (or equivalent) and Colonel (or equivalent).

Types of activity will depend on seniority.  Level one provides an introduction to the work of the service branch involved, whilst postgraduates will deal with joint working and doctrine amongst other, more strategic, considerations for defence generally.

